description.text: This is another version of a lock for the MakerGear M2 Z-axis knob, to keep the Z-stage from dropping when the motors are turned off. The problem I've had with other such locks is that I have a tendency to turn on my printer and then hit the "home Z" button without bothering to check if the lock is on or not. If it is, then the Z motor starts hammering away, and usually I have to kill the power and start over. This version is designed so that it stops the Z stage from dropping, but won't stop it from lifting. NOTE: For the M2 dual upgrade, this knob does not allow the extruder assembly to move all the way to the left. See http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:934680 for another version that solves the extruder assembly clearance problem.

Prints with no particular issues.  As designed, it works with both the older and newer style knobs.  The newer knobs are a bit smaller, so it's a little loose on the new knobs and a little tight on the old knobs.  If that's an issue, the part can be scaled accordingly.  
It would be nice if it could clear the extruder mount;  as it is, it gets in the way of the extruder going to "home X".  Since that's a tight fit, it will take more clever design work than I have time for right now.

comments.text: Having used this knob for a while, I've decided that it needs to be redesigned so that it will not prevent the extruder from moving all the way to the left.  It prevents the problem of me doing a home Z (before bed leveling) when the lock is still on, but now I've found that the more common problem is that I start a print with the lock still on (because the bed is already level, so I just go straight to printing).  The X axis homes first, and the print is just as hosed as before.  Designing it to be clear of everything in the home position while still being able to pop off by itself if the Z stage moves up will be tricky.

Installation Instructions

  • Remove support material and any stray filament from part

  • Remove filament from printer

  • Remove spring loaded arm from extruder

  • Slide filament guide over drive pulley (hobbed bolt)

  • Attach filament guide to upper left hole in stepper motor with M3 X 5mm screw

  • Re-install spring loaded arm to extruder

  • Insert filament into printer and your installation is complete

not have an extruder cooling fan it is recommended that you use an external fan to cool the extruder when printing flexible filament.
This will prevent the extruder from becoming too hot and causing the filament to jam in the small cavity in the top of the hotend.

description.text:
This is an adapter for a Central Machinery 47158 / Sieg X1 Mill to a NEMA 23 Stepper Motor. I've currently modeled the X/Y and Z mounts on the mill, the coupler, the stepper motor, and a custom X/Y bracket. After fine tuning the X/Y bracket I will create a Z bracket and add it to this project. Mill:
http://images.harborfreight.com/manuals/47000-47999/47158.pdf Stepper:
http://www.probotix.com/stepper_motors/ht23-260-4/ Coupling:
The coupling was purchased from probotix as well, but they are carrying a different coupling now.
http://www.probotix.com/mechanical_components/ Changelog:
14-June-2015: Increased holes by 10%, Shortened distance from mill to stepper, cut away a cylinder to allow room for the head of the bolt going into the mill, slightly decreased the cross-cut cylinder 20-June-2015: The updated X/Y mount is working well. The Z mount needs some adjustments. Need to increase hole size slightly, increase the spacing between the two parts where the bolts go in, and need to shorten the overall height.

The XY Brackets use 2 M6-1.00 x 50 Hex Cap Screws and 4 M4-.70 x 30 Hex Cap Screws  
The Z Bracket uses 2 M6-1.00 x 70 Hex Cap and 1 corresponding nut (one of the bolts is too close to the sidewall for the nut to fit on, but the hole in the machine is already threaded, so it is secure).  
When printing, print it horizontally to give it strength, otherwise it may break between layers.

Renosis pointed out that all this extrude/transform OpenSCAD business would render a lot faster (and produce smaller files) if I played directly with polygons. He's right.
I'm not sure how far I can take this new line of inquiry, but for a simple triangle, I can now extrude it along Z while translating and rotating in in the X-Y plane. The seams always match up, it's the exact minimum number of faces, and you can control how smooth you want the object to be directly, kinda like the $fn system variable.
The results compile instantly and render in minutes instead of hours, even for high polycounts, the STLs are tiny (183 kB) and import just fine in OpenSCAD.

This is actually pretty clean code for this series, feel free to take a look. Also, since it compiles fast, experiments are easy! GitHub repository:
https://github.com/syvwlch/Thingiverse-Projects/tree/master/ExtrudePolygon

Objective Design a structure that could be part of a future Mars colony Audience This was a 7th grade project, but could work for grades 4 - 10 Preparation This project came at the end of a science unit on the Solar System. Students had limited experience with Tinkercad.com Steps
  • Use the Internet to research the kinds of structures that might be part of a future colony on Mars
  • Students draw and describe the structure they will design (see PDF file)
  • Build your structure on Tinkercad
  • Designs were modified, if necessary, and printed
  • Students explained their designs to their classmates and the structures were assembled into a model Mars colony

title: an octave of tiny organ pipes

description.text: After I posted the organ pipe whistle http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:311 two years ago, I designed a full octave of pipes and told myself I'd post the files just as soon as I cleaned them up a little. Well, it took a few years, but I finally got around to it. These files contain 13 organ pipe whistles, not tuned to any particular standard, but they're pretty much in tune relative to each other. The files are partly optimized to reduce the number of cuts by sharing long flat edges, but this means it's a bit more work to copy and paste single parts. Design note - here's the silly way I tuned the 13 whistles: I started with a single whistle and copied it, and then doubled the length of the pipe above the fipple. Then I put those two pipes on opposite ends of a wide document and drew a diagonal line between their tops. I made 11 more copies of the pipe and distributed them equally between the little one and the big one, and then manually dragged their tops until they hit the diagonal line. Instant equal-tempered scale!

Cut from 1/8" wood (not tested on acrylic but I bet that would work too).  The two documents work well on two 24x12" sheets or five 24x4" sheets of wood, which is what I used.  
Each document has an optional engraving layer for marking numbers on all the pieces so you can keep track.  It's pretty easy to sort the pieces by size, though, so you might just skip the engraving.
For each of the 13 pipes, assemble by gluing the layers together to build up a full pipe.  (See photos for hints.)  Note that each pipe has a notch cut out of it, to allow fine tuning with a strip of metal.  I never bothered to tune my set; I just left the notches open.
If you make a set, please post a video of what they sound like!

title: Floating X carriage mount for Trinity Labs Aluminatus 1. De-couples Z axis lift from X-Y variance

description.text:
The X carriage mount decouples the Z lift lead screw in the X-Y plane. The bottom plate that the lead-screw nut mounts to can move around under the smooth rod bearings. The fork in the bottom plate goes on the smooth rod to prevent rotation of the bottom plate, so there may be some minor coupling there. I mount the smooth rod followers to the bottom two slots of the X-carriage SIMO. The Z-endstop adjuster screw matches up with the original Aluminatus Z-endstop position.  I've printed the parts in ABS without support material. They seem to work Ok, even if they're not very pretty.  
This is just an update. I've stiffened the rim of the bearing holder and adjusted the location of the lead screw hole.

I started with the Aluminatus 1 X carriage, imported the stl into openscad to get the hole alignment and sizes for reference, then used openscad to make the replacement.
The fillets around the cylinder are Bezier curves from bezier.scad.

title: J-Head Bowden Delta Printer (bowden support, all metal) with microswitch

description.text:
this is my change with support for microswitchs like http://hacker.instanet.net/Store/micro-switch-right-angle-p-42.html
or http://hacker.instanet.net/Store/micro-switch-extended-button-p-44.html I took some microswitch from a toy remote control that was broken.

You just print this, buy 3 microswitch
Add them in place with some sort of glue, if you think is needed, or double sided tape,
wire them in series so if one of them isn't clicked it will break connection.
I cut one leg of the switch, and added one into the small hole. You will need to enlarge a little bit the slot for the microswitch with a cutter, if you don't cut to much you will not need any glue.
When you mount this you will need some small springs, I took mine from some courtain holder, be creative. You can cut a spring from a pen for them. You need to put a washer on the screw, then a spring, then another washer, add the support, other washer another washer and bolt it all together. Make sure that all switches are pressed and connect the wire to the Z-probe.
When the extruder hit the bed, the microswitch contact will be broken and z-probe will be alerted. Initially the central hole was meant to be for the Fan wire, but I added a small led in the central hole in order to see when the contact is broken. This is not necessary, but makes thing a little easier to test. Please note that this is my first 3d work, and I din;t have time to test yet the actual Z-probe auto bed leveling.

description.text: Print many of the same part and connect them all together to make a long bottom for your sluicebox!

description.header:
Now added another TWO new pieces to the puzzle!
And there will be more to come :)!
Though I have not tried to print the new ones yet so bare with me, you are free to try if you want to! :)
description.text:
I realized the connection parts did not fit properly, made the old model in a hurry... Now updated and with better edges to catch the gold!
I will make more different shaped parts that can connect with themselfes to build a long sluice box with good properties to get all kinds of gold from the big ones to the fine particles! Also added some pics with sides and many connected so you can imagine how it would look :)! The measurement between the lower fastening holes ( I only use them ) is 99mm.
It was 10cm in cad but i did not account for shrinkage so after printed it became 9,9cm.
So if you need to drill holes in what ever kind of sides you are using you should use 9,9cm for that if you use a plastic prone to shrinkage as abs :)!
Or scale the print up by 0.01% I would also recommend to use some sort of rubber seal between the sidewalls and the bottom sluice parts. an old bicycle tube works fine if you cut it apart :) or some other rubber material that makes a long and flat seal. You could also use silicone or something and spread out a thin layer on the side walls and let harden and after it has hardened drill some holes etc after you've done that and then complete the sluice box :). I'll keep this as a WIP because it will probably be released more and more parts with different shapes now and then :)!

This is a try to add an additional (software controlled) fan to the Reprap Ormerod. The original fan was replaced with a more quit one, which still runs all the time to cool the heat sink. The second one is controlled over the fan output of the Duet board, using DC42 firmware.

To re-use the original screws that hold the "main-fan", I created stud holes to enter the screw heads. The cone and the the second fan are fixed with M3 screws of the proper lenght and nuts. Add some washers at the screw that holds the cone.
For the second fan two additional wires need to be inserted to the cable conduit of the hot end.
I had some issues with the hot end connector: the hot end stayed cold, but the connector reached high temperatures. Therefore I decided to add a highpower connector for RC model batteries for the heating and use the original contacts for the second fan.
Parts are printed with PLA, 0.25 mm layers, 20 % infill (it's not much to fill ...). The base was printed upside down, the cone standing at the fan mount.
